# Cairn counterfactual memory — disputes.yml TEMPLATE
#
# Copy this file to disputes.yml and edit it. disputes.yml is
# gitignored (see .gitignore) so you can author freely without
# leaking commercial-sensitive material into the repo.
#
# How the importer reads this file
# --------------------------------
# Each top-level list item is ONE dispute case. A case has an ID,
# some metadata, one or more phases (chronological steps of the
# same dispute), and optionally a case-level lesson.
#
# Every phase becomes one row in cairn_intel.decisions. All phases
# of the same case share a case_id so retrieval can pull them
# together as a single narrative.
#
# The LAST phase of a case receives the case-level
# `lessons_in_your_own_words` as its verbatim lesson. If you leave
# `lessons_in_your_own_words` blank on a case, the pipeline upgrades
# THAT SINGLE LESSON CALL to Claude Opus (not Sonnet). Opus is
# expensive — leave it blank deliberately, not by default.
#
# Field reference
# ---------------
#   case_id                    Required. kebab-case. Unique within file.
#                              Example: evri-clarion-2024
#   parties                    List of names of the parties involved.
#                              Example: [NBNE, Evri, Clarion]
#   initial_claim_gbp          Optional. The opening figure in play.
#   final_settlement_gbp       Optional. Where it ended up.
#   phases                     Required list of phase objects.
#     phase                    Required. snake_case phase label,
#                              e.g. initial_response, escalation, settlement
#     decided_at               Required. ISO date like 2024-03-15
#     context                  Required. Your narrative of what happened
#                              at this phase, 3–8 sentences, pipe-quoted
#                              so YAML keeps the line breaks.
#     chosen_path              Required. What you actually did.
#     rejected_alternatives    Optional but VALUABLE. List of paths you
#                              considered and ruled out, with reasons.
#                              THIS IS THE COUNTERFACTUAL SIGNAL.
#     outcome                  Optional. What happened next.
#     chosen_path_score        Optional. -1.0 (disaster) to +1.0 (clear win).
#                              Your own after-the-fact judgement.
#     metrics                  Optional mapping of structured numbers.
#   lessons_in_your_own_words  Optional. What you actually learned from
#                              this case, in your own words. Attached
#                              VERBATIM to the last phase's outcome —
#                              Claude does NOT rewrite it. If blank,
#                              Claude Opus generates a lesson instead.

# ── Worked example 1: case with a verbatim lesson ───────────────────
- case_id: evri-example-2024
  parties: [NBNE, Evri, ExampleClient]
  initial_claim_gbp: 1705
  final_settlement_gbp: 350
  phases:
    - phase: initial_response
      decided_at: 2024-03-15
      context: |
        The courier alleged damage on a high-value signage shipment
        and demanded the full invoice value as a claim. Their first
        settlement offer came in at roughly one fifth of the claim.
        The insurance window was closing within days, so the
        decision could not be deferred.
      chosen_path: "Rejected the first settlement offer and countered at £GBP."
      rejected_alternatives:
        - path: "Accept the initial settlement offer immediately"
          reason: "Would have set a precedent for future claims and signalled we'd capitulate under time pressure."
        - path: "Escalate straight to formal legal action"
          reason: "Too expensive for the size of the claim; also closes the door on a commercial resolution."
      outcome: |
        Settled six weeks later at roughly the middle of the range.
      chosen_path_score: 0.7
      metrics:
        settlement_gbp: 350
        days_to_resolve: 47
    - phase: escalation
      decided_at: 2024-04-05
      context: |
        After the first rejection the courier escalated and mentioned
        passing the claim to a collections agency. We held position
        and documented the case in writing, referencing the ombudsman.
      chosen_path: "Held position, documented the case for ombudsman review, and waited."
      outcome: |
        Courier backed down and proposed a revised figure within ten days.
      chosen_path_score: 0.6
  lessons_in_your_own_words: |
    Never accept the first settlement offer from a courier. Counter
    ONCE at a credible figure and then wait — the cost of waiting
    is almost always lower than the cost of capitulating. Silence
    after the counter is a negotiating tool, not a sign of failure.

# ── Worked example 2: case with NO verbatim lesson (Opus will write one) ──
- case_id: retail-colour-drift-2024
  parties: [NBNE, RetailClient]
  phases:
    - phase: initial_complaint
      decided_at: 2024-07-02
      context: |
        A retail client disputed a batch of printed panels, claiming
        colour drift. The photographic evidence they supplied was
        inconclusive. They threatened to withhold payment across three
        open invoices unless something was done.
      chosen_path: "Offered a partial reprint on the worst panel and invoiced the rest normally."
      rejected_alternatives:
        - path: "Reprint everything free of charge"
          reason: "Not justified by the available evidence; would have eaten the margin on three jobs."
        - path: "Refuse entirely and hold firm on the invoices"
          reason: "Would have ended a £40k/year relationship over a £1,500 job."
      outcome: |
        The client accepted the partial remedy and paid all three
        invoices within the original terms. The relationship continued
        the following year at the same volume.
      chosen_path_score: 0.8
      metrics:
        invoice_total_gbp: 1500
        partial_remedy_value_gbp: 400
  # lessons_in_your_own_words intentionally omitted — Opus will
  # generate a lesson from the context + chosen_path + outcome.

# Delete the two examples above and replace them with your own cases.
# Ten to twenty real cases is where retrieval starts paying off.
